annotation: Hi everyone!  Yet another round against Freddy and yet another date with Old Matey.  How did this happen well to summarise I start of with c4 which is the English Opening which controls the squares b5 and d5 and also allows for Nc3 without blocking in the c pawn.  Freddy then surprises me with b5 - a gambit.  I decide to accept the gambit well you never know if I can hang on to the gambit material and he doesn't get any play for it then despite the near 500 rating difference I may be able to get an endgame victory.  But there is the saying "Many a slip twixt cup and lip" and boy doese'nt it happen here!  Freddy mixes things up in the database and I end up developing Fou Lenoir on the wrong square d2 instead of b2.  This made one heck of a difference as I was unable to control the c column and so had to concede that to Freddy.  Freddy then won back the pawn and weakened my kingside pawn structure.  If only I could swap off the heavies.  Freddy only had pawns on the kingside and I had a remote passer - with opposite bishops that would most probably have meant two words ........ draw game ........ but the heavies stayed on.  Ironically the most active piece was wait for it ............GLENDA!!  Unfortunately she strayed from Henry's side to try to aid promotion of my remote a pawn - unfortunately allowing for a decisive and fatal invasion of the Wicked Witch of the West and that is when Henry met an ignominious end.  Anyhow on with the game.
3. Nc3 - after the b pawn is gambited there are two normal developing knight moves on both sides one to c3 and the other f6.
6. Nxb5 - seems to consolidate white's pawn advantage doubleton removed and I have an outside passed a pawn.
9.0-0 - so far so natural.  Normal routine development on both sides and I think I have equality here.   However it is 2 moves down the line that it starts to go mouldy on me.
11. Bd2?! - would b3 have been a better try here?
13. Nc3? - on second thoughts I wonder if it was this move which was the lemon.  Would Rc1 have been a better plan here?  At least I would have bagged the c column first.
17. Nxe4 - I would have loved to have backed up the knight with Rc1 but the a pawn would have been left hanging and the b pawn would have been left weak.

18. a4 - this pawn move releases the rook from the defense of the a5 pawn now it is defended by ........ guess who ........ well who else ......... Glenda!  Always on that back rank defending pawns.  Right now she would just lurve to be on g7 but she would need to be teleported there!

22. Rb1 - after a plethora of exchanges Freddy has regained his pawn and busted up my kingside pawn structure.  I try to defend my valuable a4 passer by attacking the witch and then placing Fou Leblanc onto b5 next move.

24. Qd3 - Glenda moves but I think that over the next 4 moves I had the opportunity to put a rook on c1 to neutralise the power of Freddy's rook on the c column.  I could have then moved Henry to h2 and then used my other rook to try and help Glenda attack the enemy king.  But silly me did not do this and I paid the price.  Do you the jury agree?

28. h4? - a well intentioned move this move is intended to try and open the g column and then place a rook on the g file and then Glenda and the rook neatly line up on the enemy king.  But there is the little matter of the Wicked Witch of the West.

29. Qg5 - offering a queen trade but Freddy's next move puts the blockers on that.  The h4 pawn will fall.  In hindsight it would have been better to have let it go - at least I would have avoided getting Freddied later on.
31. ........ Rc2 - invasion!
33. Qb7 - this loses spectacularly - the plan was to try and shepherd that remote passer to a8 to become Glenda 2 but now comes my doom!
34. Rh1 - defending the loose h pawn but allowing something worse.  Here come some creeping moves on the light squares by the Wicked Witch.
34. ....... Qf5 - here she comes!
35. .......... Qg4 - here she comes!  Notice the rook on d1 is en prise.
36. ......... Qf3 - here she is!  Oooh nasty nasty now the rook on h1 is en prise.  I move the rook to h2 thinking I have covered everything but here comes a stunning Master Pseudo-Sacrifice.......

37. .......... Rxf2 !!!  Here Freddy announced mate in 11 beginning with:- 38. Rxf2 Qh1  39. Ke2 Rc2  40. Kd1 Rc1  41. Ke2 Qxe1  42. Kf3 Qd1  43. Re2 Qf1  44. Rf2 Qh3  45. Ke2 Qg4  46. Rf3 Qg2  47. Rf2 Rc2  48. Kd1 Qxf2 49. Qc8  Rxc8 50. Be2 Qg1  51. Bf1 Qxf1  52. Kd2 Bc1#.  Like a good little girl I start to play out the moves.  Freddy sets them up as conditionals.  I play out the moves because I will have a hands on tuition on how to conduct a king hunt to the death.  I am very inexperienced at this sort of thing.  I have mounted a few successful mating attacks on lower rated players but with Freddy announcing #11 this all seems so crude and amateurish compared to this awesome thing that Freddy is about to show me.  I suppose the first step to being able to mount a successful mating attack is to be on the receiving end of one!

41. Kd2 - now here is a fingerslip - I should have played Ke2 but this turns out to be a happy fingerslip because although I still cop Old Matey I choose the quickest and least painful route.  For after the game I was able to access my personal db call up this game and analyse what would have happened had I continue to play along with Freddy.  The answer - I would have lost all yes all of my pieces bar Henry.  The bishop checkmate at the end would have been very pretty but I would have hated to give up all my pieces first so at least I was spared that.
43. ......... Qxe3#.  An ignominious and undignified end for me pore Ole 'Enry.  But I will be back Freddy never fear!  Joanne

This game was no easy win for me!  The middlegame got very complicated and I very nearly got Glenda trapped.  Luckily I managed to force a queen trade later on which gradually turned the tide in my favour.  Finally we ended up in a K & P ending where even though I was a pawn up I had to avoid one last trick from Bob - I pull out a hidden talent from my sleeve the joblock!  This finally forced Bob's resignation on the grounds of ruinous loss of material.
2. ....... c6 - the QGD - Slav Defense - I decide to back up my c pawn rather than exchange on c4.
5. .......... e6 - looking a little symmetrical.
8. ......... Qc8 - Glenda's menial task for the day - guard b7 pawn!
11. Rac1 - putting rook on the same file as Glenda - good idea!
14. .......... Bg6 - I decide to preserve Fou Leblanc - turns out I made the right choice later on.
16. ......... Nf6 - trying to decongest my position.  Steed eyes up a possible landing on e4.
19. ........... Qf5 - and Glenda still cannot get away from defending pawns!  This time she is called for the defense of the h5 square.
20. ......... Ne4 - mission accomplished although that steed will exchange itself for the enemy counterpart next turn.
23. ......... Qd3 - now Glenda will be lost but thankfully in exchange for the Wicked Witch of the West!
26. Be2 - driven back.
30. .......... g4 - now I try and put the squeeze on.  Are the Expert lessons starting to take some effect?
32. ........ g3  - Onward Christian Soldiers!
37. ......... Rg8 - bringing the a8 rook finally into play on Move THIRTY-SEVEN!
39. ........ Bg5 - the kingside in white's arc is becoming a Crowded House!
43. ......... Rgxf4 - white drops a second pawn but ......

45. ......... Kg6 - I must get Henry in on the action here he covers quite a few defensive squares to avoid an enemy rook invasion.  Bob now chooses a move which allows more simplification in my favour.
47. ........ Kxg5 - and now if you are a pawn up in a K & P ending you are virtually on a home run but there are still a few things to watch out for before the game is sewn up!
49. Kg2 - best move now comes some pawn play leading to putting Bob in a zugzwang.
51.  ........... b5 - and here is that little pawn push the joblock which does the trick here because Bob realises he is in a zugzwang and waves the white flag!  Job done folks!
Rook sacrificed for pawn advancement!   I'm playing white and perhaps played one of my better games here.
I normally don't open backside like this but since he's yet to place any threat in the middle I figure why not.
I don't quite understand why he's letting me have the center of the board.

I like this move a lot I use it quite frequently to get the kings rook more envolved in the middle of the board.  I will wait against some players to see if he castles I figure this guy is pretty good so i will go ahead and bring him out.
I'm not sure why he decided to take g2 before qxf6.
ahh....the useful e1 rook
My ferocious pawns are beginning to burden my opponent.  lol
ok now he has a problem.
he goes ahead and moves here figuring to take 1 rook and my bishop
I let him take a1 while guarding f2  and potentially losing both rooks
now his rook is in a bind
I wait to take seeing something even more magneficent.  Queen/rook diagonal is in need of some help  HAHA
take obviously he'll have to take mine and I get both his rooks
BOOM!
the funs not over sucker come away from the rook
Now it's all over but the crying...
get rid of that nasty booger
Good game mate!

This was Freddy's proof that 7...Bd6 is not such a bad move really.  I still think it sucks but I have to admit that he makes it work in this game!  He played "conditional moves" up to that point then we got down to business.
so far as in my Oxford and District League game against Heather Lang.  Now Freddy varies not allowing my sac on g5
so I continue with my standard development
and Freddy puts the question to my B heading for a powerful outpost on f4
naturally I swap it off as it has no other useful moves.

? Freddy commented during that game that 14. d4 was much better at this point.  My N soon completes its journey to g3 but then swaps off on e4 which it could have done from d2 so I'd wasted two tempi on that manoeuvre.
as anticipated in my game against Heather (but it didn't materialise in that game)
! vigorously played.  He doesn't only play "rope-a-dope"!

Now I spot an "opportunity" that in retrospect was nothing like one and quickly go down in ignominy.  Instead I should have looked carefully at what Freddy was planning and considered how to avoid mate on g2!
?? hoping to skewer K and Q on the diagonal but Black is way ahead of me here
?  19.g3 was better according to Freddy
? 20. Qxf3 was not much better because of 20...Nh3  followed by 21. ... Rxf3 but now Freddy announced Mate in 3
and now there is nothing to prevent ...Qg2# so I play a token move to allow him the satisfaction.

The Grob Opening. Coincidentally I had just about finished "King's Gambit: The Story of a Father a Son and the World's Most Dangerous Game" By Paul Hoffman. Hoffman spent an entire chapter on the practitioners of the Grob and had some unsavory opinions of them. Swindlers would be a common theme. So I was hot to beat this guy.

Reinforcing the pawn. A weak move in retrospect. c6 appears better now. I as a practitioner of the Nimzo Larsen am aware that his goal is to fianchetto the rook on a8 (at least for now later I forget this) so delaying the attack on d5 is what I need to do.
Adds to the attack on d5
Sets up for a discovered check. I'm in a bit of a bind here.
If he takes the Knight at least I can put pressure on the Queen with Bxd7.
I'm not hot to trade Queens here but I don't see a lot of other options.
I can only see one real hope here. Hopefully I can pull it off.
First part of it is in place.
Will he miss it?
A Bishop for a little bait
He takes the bait.
Out hustled the hustler.

Hi everyone!  Another session with Master Freddy which ended in a trouncing.  Behold Master Freddy gives me another lesson in how to execute a checkmating sequence so it all ends with me copping Old Matey from him yet again!  He starts off with d4 and I respond with an unusual reply c5 which is called The Old Benoni.
4. Nf3 - Freddy steers the opening into the Woozle Defense whatever that is ... it's one of his fav's ..... sigh and double sigh!
6. ......... a6 - to prevent an enemy knight or bishop settling on d5 and preparing a possible b5.  Freddy puts the blockers on this idea by playing his pawn to a4 next turn.

8. ......... Bf5 - I trusted the World DB and Freddy exposed this as a weak time wasting move.  Freddy moved his knight to h4 and I had to either back up or move the bishop.  I chose to move Fou Leblanc to d7.  In retrospect would Qc1 have been a better choice.  Jury please advise.
11. ....... Ne8 - a Sneaky Knight move here (I am a member of that team and Gothicgirl is my skipper!) but (a test for the jury) what does it threaten?
16. ......... Qd8 - after a plethora of exchanges Glenda returns to d8 and Nf6 is prepared for my next turn.
19. .......... Qc7.  Next move I will play Nd7 and my rooks will be connected.  The knight will then hop on to f6.  But wait...... Freddy has other ideas!

20. Bxh7  - ............. A SACRIFICE ON H7!  Yup it turns out to be the bog standard Greek Gift (Trojan Horse) sacrifice.  I accept it because if I don't I will be a pawn down without sufficient play for it but a post match pm from Freddy stated that this would have been the lesser of the two evils!
22. .......... Nd7 - finally I manage to develop that horse but I end up in deep horse dung!
23. Ra3 - let's begin with a rook swinger.  This rook is heading for h3 with a deadly line up of the Wicked Witch of the West and her castle.  That is a sure recipie for copping Old Matey.
24. ....... Henry tries to escape but to no avail.  Freddy plays his queen to g5 and tells me that I am going to be checkmated (Oh No not that again!).
26. Rxf7  .......... but Oh Yes!  Freddy now announces #3 (he did tell me he had a # in 13 before I played g6).  Could you the jury spot this mate in 13?

27. .......... Ke8 - I am 6 points up in material but that is SFA when Henry is about to get the kiss of death!  Just before I played Ke8 Freddy asked me to spot the mate in 3.  Here are the other two variations that lead to the mate in 3:-

Variation A

27. Rh7  Kg8 
28. Qxg6  Kf8 
29. Qf7# 

Variation B

27. Rh7  Kf8 
28. Qf4  Kg8 
29. Qf7# 

Variation B1

27. Rh7  Kf8 
28. Qf4  Ke8 
29. Qf7#
28. Qe7# - it's all over folks!

You would think that 1750  players would be above missing or walking into basic tactics wouldn't you?  But not jstevens1 oh no.  In this game I played to the level of my OTB rating - 1200!  In fact from some 1200 players I have seen better!  So Jo time to get back to basics!  The game starts off with Ion playing d4 and me trying to set up some flank action with the Modern Defence which is the response g6.
3. ........ d6 - transposes into a Pirc/Robatsch Defence.
6. Nxd4 - I break up Ion's impressive pawn wall and now I concentrate on simple development.
9. ......... f5 - a recommended db move but I think this is the start of a recipie for disaster!

12. ......... Be6 - so far db but now Ion takes me out of it with this move.  I now take back with the wrong unit I think.  Jury would you agree that Nxf5 attacking the Wicked Witch of the West have been a better recapture?

14. ........ c5?  this move is intended to drive away the Wicked Witch but jury do you agree that c6 would have been a better move here?  At least it would have blocked off that light squared bishop's diagonal.

16. .......... Rf7 - the only way to avoid losing material outright is to block the check on d5 with the rook - although the rook is pinned the Witch cannot take the b pawn as in moving the witch would release the rook from the pin and so the witch would be no more.  No such luck!
17. Rad1 - the pressure mounts on my d6 pawn which becomes a new target.
17. ........... Qb6 - counterattack on the b2 pawn but it simply doesn't wash!
19. .......... Rdd7 - an amazing array of pins here!  As an exercise perhaps you the jury would like to tell me how many pins there are and what is pinned to what!
20. ......... Qd8 - I sink further into deep ordure!

21. ......... Rxd5 - I play the move but then decided to throw in the sponge because Glenda will fall next move and my rook will have to take on d1.  The recapture will leave Ion an R & P up.  I would resign against someone 300 points lower than me never mind higher with this kind of deficit.  A sorry tale.

Hi everyone just to share another good result in my 1700-1800 tournament.  I have now managed 4 points out of the first 5 games with 3 wins and 2 draws.  This is my latest win.  We start off with a standard Ruy Lopez leading to a variation called the Leonhardt Variation.
5. ......... Be7 - a conservative developing move clearing the way for kingside castling.  This is the start of the Leonhardt Variation.
8. c3 - creating an escape hatch for his bishop thus avoiding the famous Noah's Ark Trap.
10. .......... c5 - I try to claim space on the queenside.

13. ......... g6 - this move seems to weaken my kingside position but the g6 move does stop white from plonking a knight in on f5.  Next move Fou Lenoir will move in to f8 to strengthen my castled position.
17. Qd2 - the Wicked Witch of the West and the enemy dsb have my h6 pawn in their sights.  Henry now adds protection to this pawn.
18. d4 - a move which strikes out in the centre but the downside is is that as a result of a plethora of exchanges his e4 pawn is going to be very weak.  This factor will swing the game in my favour.

24. ......... Rde8 - hope you can all follow that frenetic action!  I decided to double rooks on the e file and keep up the pressure on b2.  Crucially my hind rook moves onto a white square so that black's dsb cannot fork it against my knight on the rim.
25. ......... Rxe4 - one pair of rooks is exchanged.
27. .......... Re2 - the pile up on the b2 pawn is relentless.  Note that if he advances it his dsb is hanging to my knight which has come off the rim and is certainly not dim!
31. Rd3 - tries to save his a pawn but my next move .......
31. ..... Bb2 - unsaves it!
33. ........ Rxa3 - 2 lovely remote ebony queenside passers!

34. ...... Kg7 - maybe this move wastes a tempo but if I am unable to promote either b or a pawn and my rook is able to take one or more of his kingside pawns then I want to preserve my own kingside pawns!
10. ......... Ra4 - 1st step in a plan to gradually nurse one of the queenside pawns to Glendadom!

36. ........ b4 - but I do not have to think about this plan any more because my opponent decides enough is enough and he hands me 9.6 mega handy rating points!  What a good start to the weekend!  Joanne
Here's another thrashing!  Freddy continues with his rope-a-dope strategy.
heading for a fianchetto and a probable King's Indian setup
We're both playing at a distance here.  I'm trying to keep it as tight as my opponent...
At last I crack!  Contact is made.
?  Looks harmless enough but leaves a hole in the heart of Black's position.

!!  Completely unexpected and devastating to my position.  How can I continue to develop normally?  Neither N has a sensible move.  My QB can't move and if I play my b-pawn the c-pawn falls.  In retrospect perhaps 11...Nh5 is better than the move played.
! Saddling me with doubled pawns that completely cramp my position.
I was starting to feel that I'd nearly sorted out my problems at this stage... WRONG!
The N needed a decent square to retreat to.  I couldn't oppose the a-pawn with mine because the N would have been left undefended.  Perhaps Rad8 would have been better here.
Now this R is doomed.  Move it to f7 and White's N attacks it to f6 and my e5-pawn falls (perhaps not such a bad thing) or 18. Be7!
I play along anyway.
My position is becoming quite comical all huddled up like the pigs in their little house hiding from the Big Bad Wolf!
even more so!  Note that as my R can't go anywhere White leaves it be choosing instead to impose more torture till he's got nothing better to do.
and even more little piggies huddle together!
now a new threat: the a-pawn will promote if I don't stop it.  I have a choice: swap or advance my b-pawn which would probably be followed by 26. Rd7 (or maybe 26. Bxf6 followed by 27. Rd7)
trying to avoid unnecessary swapping when material down but it makes no difference
Now what can I do?  In the absence of anything more constructive I try to "do nothing" while centralising my K and hoping that an opportunity to mobilise my Bs may arise.
missing the threat.
announcing mate in 2

In this game White is attacking on the kingside and Black prepares a counterattack in the center. However strategy gives way to tactics when White captures a poisoned pawn and traps his own queen. All comments are most welcome!
Of course White cannot take on e5 because of Qd4 when both his knight and pawn on e4 are hanging. This would mean losing the pawn as well as the right to castle.
The pawn on e5 is still immune so Black continues developing.

Now the pawn finally had to be protected. The move 6...f6 somehow weakens the diagonal a2-g8 but this is of no consequence: White's light-squared bishop is off the board and his queen is not in position to control that diagonal.
Black continues developing. It is not clear where the bishop should go so it is better to first develop the knight.
So it becomes clear that White is preparing a kingside attack. This move is made with the idea of making the move f4 possible.
Since there are still no threats Black continues developing and tries to control the center. This will become important later on.

Probably clearing the g1 square for the rook. As it happens however White never actually places the rook on g1. It seems to me that White wastes too much time preparing the attack and leaves his queenside undeveloped.
Controlling f4 with the knight and freeing one more square for the queen. Black's knight was weak where it was and on g6 it controls more squares and also helps protect the kingside.
Controlling the square f4 once more.
Black simply continues developing. This move connects the rooks and eyes the h3 pawn which might prove a weakness later on.
Black takes with the knight in order to swap it off. Reducing White's material will help blunt his attack. Also less pieces means more scope for the two bishops that Black has at his disposal.
This decision is difficult to understand. White gives away his good bishop and in my opinion he should have captured with the knight to keep the bishop on board.
Simply moving the bishop to safety. This bishop does not have too many squares to move to but it does control some central squares and is a good defender of Black's king.

And so Black starts preparing his counterplay. Since White is attacking on the kingside it is best to counter with an attack in the center. Combined with Black having doubled pawns on the c-file this suggests that Black should try to exchange his c6 pawn for White's c2 pawn by capturing on d3 when the recapturing backward pawn on d3 would be weak. Since White has no dark-squared bishop anymore the square in front of it would be weak as well. Therefore Black prepares the push c5 and also positions the bishop where it eyes the kingside as well.
Making the planned pawn push.
White's first real threat: N:f6  loses the queen for Black.
I have the impression that White does not have a clear plan of attack. It looks as if he is waiting for Black to make a mistake that will allow him to win the game...

...and meanwhile Black is following his plan of counterattacking in the centre. Playing c4 immediately would not be that good because White could simply play d4 and evade the capture. The two central pawns could then prove to be quite strong. So Black decides to first strengthen his grip on the d file. His plan is to play Be5 to make heavy pieces control the d file and only then to play c4.
This pin makes sure that the threatening pawn will disappear from the board.
White silently attacks the b7 pawn.

Black sees the attack on the b7 pawn but decides that this is better than capturing with the pawn. After 20...f:e5 21.Ne2 Black must take care of his f7 bishop and this gives White time to blockade the weak e pawn when Black's dark-squared bishop is miserable as are his pieces on the d-file. And now if 20...N:e5 21.f:e5 Ne2 22.Bd5 saves the bishop and prevents the blockade attacking the queen at the same time and also screening b7 from attack. At this point I saw that 21.Q:b7 B:f4 22.R:f4 would make White's pieces not cooperate well and found this sufficient compensation for the pawn lost and so did not really expect White to take the b7 pawn.

And yet she did! Here I began to think how to exploit White's queen's poor position and noticed that it will be trapped. After 21...B:f4 22.R:f4 Bd5 White's queen has two squares: a6 and a7. After 23.Q:a6 Ra8 attacks the queen which has no place to go. And if 23.Qa7 then 23...Qd6 attacks the rook covers all queen's escape squares and at the same time threatens 24...Ra8 that will win the queen.
So I happily moved on with my combination.

Here I began to think about the planned move 22...Bd5 again and noticed the following possibility: 22...Bd5 23.Q:a6 Ra8 24.N:f6. This attacks my queen as well. If I play 24...g:f6 then 25.Q:f6  Qg7 (forced otherwise Black gets mated) 26.Raf1 and Black has a piece for three pawns but his pawn structure is shambles and White's pieces seem stronger. I couldn't believe that White's badly coordinated forces could be that effective and kept searching for something. And then I finally found that 24.N:f6 loses to 24...Q:h3 ! 25.Kg1 (the g-pawn cannot recapture because it is pinned by the bishop on d5) 25...Q:g2#.
And so I did play 22...Bd5.
And here White makes the move that I thought destroys my combination but in the end found it does not. Moreover this just hastens White's defeat.
And now the king has to go to g1 and will be mated on g2. It's all over.
French
Burn variation
hmm... Still book?
Better to develop the bishop than o-o-o
Blocking the d-file for the time being
!  I believe this is becoming standard much in the way you would play the Yugoslav attack against the dragon.
hmm...Is Nf6 better?
reacting to his counter play was bad.
Now his pieces are free and active
Rxe6 looks ugly and Black can have a better position after QxRe6; Nxe6...RxQd3 and black is a piece for the better
! Black has created a luft in his fortress
Black resign
Here's a short sharp lesson from Freddy!  I adopt my usual policy of avoiding 1. e4 against stronger opponents...
Freddy did tell me what opening this was but I was none the wiser...
so I decide to play "sensible" opening moves first developing the KN and opposing Black's N
to deter the B from coming to g4
Black calmly develops his KN
provoking me to play the move I'd prevented him from playing.  This is like the Torre Attack
and this is a common response to the Trompowski which I'm used to encountering as Black so I felt I was on slightly more familiar ground now though I don't play the Tromp myself.

One of my favourite chess writers Yelena Dembo advises never to retreat!  Somewhat extreme but there is sense in there if you like an attacking style.  Rather than retreat or bolster up my B more I develop another piece while leaving my c-pawn freedom to move.
Freddy whips off my B giving himself the only B pair on the board.
Naturally I recapture but this N is somewhat exposed and unsupported
so Black counter-attacks in the centre.  The pawn can't be defended effectively with a pawn or N so I counter-attack Black's N
and Black seizes the opportunity to win the pawn tying up my K-side at the same time
I need to resume my development but I didn't have to play this pawn two squares.  I could have allowed him to push my N around with 10...e4 but I didn't fancy that much.
Perhaps 11. Bc4 would have restrained Black's pawn centre
Black gets castling in first so his opening play has gained him at least one tempo
Not fancying running into a brutal kingside attack via ...Qg6 and ... Bxh3 I contemplate castling queenside though this looks no better with Black having that open file to b2
For the time being I can defend the b-pawn and pretend to threaten the doubled pawns
belatedly trying to control the a2-g8 diagonal and potentially block Black's attack on b2

but now Black attacks g2 and castling kingside looks too risky.  On the other hand if I connect my rooks and he takes on g2 I can chase the Q and draw a bead on his castled king's position.  There's a terrible problem with my next move though.  I really should have studied the position more carefully.
Oh dear.  Freddy snaps up this central pawn immediately.  I'm two pawns down with nothing to show for it.  The Big Bad Wolf has just had to let me make mistakes.

Now b2 is the target in earnest.  My Q cannot defend from c3.  18. Qd2 might defend followed by c3 but the B would be hanging.  Perhaps I should attack the Q with 18. g3.  After the Q moves I can play 19. Qd2
? missing the immediate threat while concentrating on the longer term threat.
! Horrible double attack
as good as resigning really
A whole piece and two pawns down there's no point carrying on.  Perhaps rather than criticise others' efforts I should concentrate on removing errors from my own game.

Ding-a-ling!  Here is round 7 against Master Freddy (easy 19).  I decide to start off with a Reti and see how he responds to it.  He decides to go Reti v Dutch.  This is a rare response to the Reti and Freddy takes me out of the database after move 4.  So only moves 2-4 were database moves.  The rest were my own - so let the action unfold ......
1. ............ f5 - this is the Dutch v Reti an interesting response - Freddy is trying to mix things up here probably trying to get a pawn break from the flank.
5. Nbd2 - here I decide to go for quick development.  Although this knight move blocks in Fou Lenoir it does contest the square e4 where I think Freddy would just lurve to put his horsie!
8. Bb2 - after an exchange of pawns Fou Lenoir finds a nice little diagonal pointing at the black rook on h8.

9. Nd4 - my knight evades the pawn thrust and finds an outpost on d4.  Black put his bishop on e7 next move of course if he tries to drive my knight off d4 with c5? then he will drop the b5 pawn.  After this move which prepares castling for black I decide to create a flight square for the knight with e3 - it stops that e pawn in his tracks!
12. a4 - I will not be bullied! - I decide to strike out here by challenging on the flank.
14. Ne5 - I decide to up the ante a bit - pile up on that backward c6 pawn but alas Freddy has an answer to this!
14. ........... Qe8 - such as Qe8 backing up that c pawn.  I now put the question to his b pawn.
16. Bxc3 - I split up his queenside pawn structure and keep mine together so far so good.

19. Qc2 - connects rooks and prepares a possible rook move to d1.  Mmm in retrospect maybe I should have moved that king rook to d1 next move instead of Rac1 - think I gave Freddy a tempo with that move.
24. Be5 - Oh oh I am about to lose a pawn here but I will make life as difficult as possible for Freddy by putting the hind black rook en prise.

28. ........ Bb5 - after a few exchanges black moves his bishop onto a good square and I now have to decide where to put Fou Lenoir - I decide on h6 after all it restricts the enemy king and if that rook should leave the second rank well Glenda is just itching to land on g7 to deliver a revenge checkmate.
30. Rd1 - seizing the open file but ....
33. Qa1 - Freddy pointed out that the rook trade was a mistake in the chat after I took on d7.  At the time I saw nothing better.
35. .......... Kf7 - Freddy now starts to centralise his king for the endgame.  I must try to do likewise with mine but wait there's an enemy bishop controlling f1.
38. f3 - mmm maybe I should have taken on d3 at least I would not have dropped a piece.
39. Bd2 - trying to avoid exchanging down to a pure K & P ending but allowing something much much worse.

40. ........ exf3  - a decoy tactic that loses Frere Leblanc as Henry will have to abandon protection of him.  Those two enemy bishops were just to powerful.  I now wave the white flag and look forward to any feedback the jury has on this one -  cheers - Joanne

A Variante Najdorf da Defesa Siciliana uma linha aguda que exige plena atencao dos jogadores.
Iniciando o Ataque Ioguslavo deixando claro o rumo da partida onde ha uma luta de roques opostos.
Escolhedo a variante Dragao...
Lance tentador mas prematuro! Um erro. Deveriam antes trocar os cavalos para fazer o lance da partida.
Correto seria 11.... Nxd4 12. Bxg7 Nxf3 13. gxf3 Kxg7 com clara vantagem.
14... Na5 era mais efetivo na posicao.
Correto era 15... b4 com certa iniciativa na partida.
O lance que ganha a partida.
Neutralizando as ameacas imediatas mas com jogo nitidamente inferior. E as brancas perderam por tempo. Uma continuacao simples e ganhadora era 19. h6+ K~8 20. Bxa8...
Beginning the so-called Grand Prix Attack popular for its inaugurating a K-side attack.
... Possibly this is the response that means that the Grand Prix will never supersede White's main lines of the Sicilian!
An unusual response that gambits White's e-pawn.  But White has something more spectacular already in mind...
Why not?
According to plan.  Also possible was 4.Ne5.
A straightforward attack on f7.  Black could simply block this with 5...e6 but there's nothing wrong with developing a piece to drive back the c4-bishop is there?
Apparently White must play 6.Be2 if he doesn't want to give up more material...

(!!?)  Giving up the queen for the sake of keeping his attack on f7!?  White's development has hardly begun. too!  Incidentally 6.Bxf7+  would have transposed into the game continuation.  Either way White is speculating very heavily!
There's no real choice.  Black has to test White's idea.
Forking K and N which will ensure White at least gets a second minor piece for his queen.  Still he needs a third to restore the material balance!

(!?) One has to ask what would White have played had the king returned to e8?  Would White have settled for a perpetual (9.Bxf7 ) or taken the fork (9.Nf7?! Qd4! say)?  It seems the latter course would have been very risky -  too risky perhaps?  The game might have ended in a draw right here!
However Black was not wrong at this point in fancying her chances of surviving to win.

Time to assess the position.  White has N B for the Q.  Although a long way from completing his development White has two pieces in action with forking threats at e6 and f7.  Black meanwhile pretty much has to begin all over again just to activate her game.  White has gained a great deal in time for his large material investment.

(!?) Dodging both forks at once - a sensible plan.  But another idea was to allow one of the forks to happen: 9...Qd6!? 10.Nf7!? Qxf4 11.Nxh8 Qxg4 12.0-0 Nc6.  Since much of White's temporal and spatial advantage would disappear with the win of the exchange it would seem he might have had to come up with a different plan 10.Ne6  say.
Probably safest.  Had she played 10...Kd6 this might have happened: 11.Nc3 Qg6  12.h3 Nd7  13.f5 ... 14.Nxe4  with a strong-looking attack.
Aiming for c4 and check.
Creating a hidey-hole for himself...
(!?)  Trying to open a file directed at the Black King.  Maybe White felt that 12.Nc4  Ka7 13.Nc7 Qg6 14.Bh3 offered insufficient return.

Again playing safe.  But taking on b4 was worth a look: 12...cxb4 13.Nc4  Ka7 14.d3 Nc6 15.Be3  Kb8 16.Bb6 (threatens Bc7 ) ...a5 (an attempt to create room for the BK) 17.Bc7  Ka7 (17...Kc8 18.Nb6#) 18.Bb6  Kb8 (18...Ka6 19.Nc7#) and what seems to be a perpetual.  Had White more than this if Black took the pawn?  I haven't found anything so far!

Charging onward!  See how Black is being given no time to bring out her pieces. But White's game is developing almost as slowly: yet to castle and still to bring out the Q-side pieces.  Meanwhile what might have been the consequences of opening the b-file? 13.bxc5 Qc6 (say) 14.Rb1 Nd7 15.Nc4 Qa4 and Black has some threats of her own.

This queen is just about Black's only active piece and it looks difficult to bring the others into play.  What is intriguing about all this is that it's hard to see how White can make good the loss of his queen; and equally difficult to fathom how Black can survive the bind on her game.  Are both losing??

The most logical consolidation.  But can White accelerate his attack on the other flank by offering more material?  14.b6  Kxb6 15.Nc4  (15.Rb1  might be worth a look) 15...Ka7 (no choice) 16.Ne5  Qe8 (...Qh4  seems to lead nowhere) 17.Rb1 Nc6 (17...Nd7!? 18.Nxd7!? Qxd7 19.Nxc5 Qc7 20.Rxb7  Qxb7 21.Nxb7 Kxb7 22.Bf5 with an ending difficult to assess)  18.Nxc5 Nd8 19.Bd7 Qh5 20.Nxe4... and White looks to have a fine game.
Developing a piece at last.  Black's problem has been that White has given her little chance to bring out her pieces...
...but in saying that one has to admit that White has had to employ pieces already developed.  Now comes a lull in the battle as reserves are called up.

(!?) So far Black has done nothing wrong that I can see but one feels a bit uncomfortable with this move.  However Black had to do something about her K-side and this move frees the g-pawn should she get the chance to advance it and bring out her bishop.  But maybe ...h6 was worth a look keeping the knight out of g5 and thereby making it harder for White to bring the h3-bishop into e6.  Such a  regrouping by White does happen later on.
Pinning the g7-pawn and tying down Black's K-flank.
(?!) Now had White chosen he could have carried out at once the regrouping earlier mentioned: 17.Ng5 Nf6 18.Be6.
(!?)  A 'mysterious' rook move.  Did White envisage breaking out with his d-pawn or was this played against a possible 17...Qd5 attacking d2?  A difficult move to understand I find.
Playing almost as if he hadn't a care in the world... ;-)
(!?) Possibly Black ought to have been seeking ways to unravel her K-side.  18...g6 or maybe 18...h6 offered some prospects of breaking out of the bind.
I suspect a rethink has taken place since White's 17th...
Good: centralisation - but also eyeing a couple of loose White pawns...

Discovering an attack against Black's c8-rook and threatening a fork against her other major pieces -  this looks devastating.  Does that mean Black's previous was a mistake after all?  I'm not sure it does.  It was looking likely that to free up her game Black would have to give back something.  Now with 20....Qxd2 21.Bxc8 Nxc8 22.Bc1 Qd5 Black might have gained time enough to complete her development.
(?) Wrong pawn methinks...
(!) Now Black must shed material.  How best to do this?

(?) Quite understandable attempt to cut her losses but it might have been better to have kept her most active piece and let a rook go instead.  After 21...Qd5 22.Be6  Qxd2 23.Bxg8 e3 Black at least has some counterplay.
After this capture it is hard to see how Black can survive.

Although material parity has been approximately restored White has retained his spatial and temporal advantages.  Black's K-side is so tied up that White is effectively playing with a rook and bishop extra.
(!) Centralisation! Also good was 26.Ne5 but the move played is more effective and the more visually pleasing.
Closing in for the kill.  Black is busted.  I gather Joanne considered resigning hereabouts but agreed to play out the mate.
Heralding a mate in 5...
According to the mating sequence already envisaged.  It turns out that Black's previous move allowed a different slightly quicker one.  Can you find it?  [Answer: 27.Nb5  mates in three.]
A non-check but mate can't be stopped.

A very difficult and tense game for both players I suspect.  White had to make good a large material investment; Black to find ways to free up her game.  Maybe White has the most fun in this kind of game?  I think Black was doing fine up until her 20th move (...Qxa2?).  It shows how double-edged games like this can suddenly capsize into a disaster for one side.

A fun game against a friend I play black and build a crushing pawn advantage on the queenside then screw it all up and watch it go up in smoke.
White chose the Vienna Game and I responded with the Max Lange Defense.
3. g3 is known as the Paulsen Variation and my reply breaks from the main lines - from here I'm exploring new ground (new to me anyway and not much in the Game DB).
Charging into the center.
Charging more.
At this point I feel like black is doing well. 3 pieces developed to only 2 for white and a more open and mobile position.

Trying to play by opening principles of not moving any piece twice unless I have to. I felt that taking white's bishop removes one of my developed pieces and puts the white queen on a stronger square. Also this move sets a bit of a trap. White shouldn't exchange bishops.
But he did.
And now it cost white a pawn and a second white pawn is in danger.

A little bit of center liquidation. At this point only 11 moves into the game I'm already thinking about exchanging away as many white pieces as I can so that I can exploit my queenside pawn majority.

A small blunder by white. None of his options were great. Moving his king limits his castling ability but was his best choice. Blocking with his queen loses the white rook on a1. But the move played loses the white pawn on d3.
Up by two pawns with a 3 to 1 advantage on the queenside the only thing standing between me and an easy win is all the white pieces. Fortunately white seems willing to trade them off.
Now a 3 to 0 advantage on the queenside with three supported adjacent passed pawns. There is absolutely no way for black to fail to promote one ore more of these lucky pawns right?

I think 19. Nd7 would have been strong for white. I wouldn't want him to take my knight on f6 and break up my pawn formation when he has a 4 to 3 advantage and open up my king to all of his pieces on the kingside. Which means I would have played 19. ... Nxd7 which would allow him to get a rook on the 7th rank and create problems for my queenside pawns. White didn't do it and now I prevent it with 19. ... Be6.

Here I miscalculate. I had a sneaky plan of putting white in check on the back rank and then pinning the white bishop after he blocks then winning it by attacking the pinned bishop with my own bishop. It was not until after I had committed to this foolhardy plan that I realized there was no way I could complete that plan before white could play Kg2. Fortunately I had a fallback plan but I am still doomed to watching most of my queenside advantage go up in smoke.

I was facing a checkmate in 1 and I have no good attacks against white. I make a hole that is the opposite color of the only white bishop and that his knight can never threaten without facing a pawn capture or blocking his rook on the 8th rank. I am thinking about 24. ... Ng5 which then trades knights and allows me to play Be2 to win the white bishop or which chases the knight away allowing Bc4 to win the white bishop - but I doubt white will allow this.
My careless plan on my 20th move cost me a pawn and decimated my queenside advantage. At least I am well poised for an attack. This move threatens to win the white bishop with Nd2
Threatens to win a pawn. It looks to be fully protected but it is not.

White believed his pawn was safe but I showed him the error in his logic. Now if 28. Nxf3 Bxf3  and black has still won the pawn and has exchanged some of white dwindling material. If 29. Kxf3 Rxf1  and black has still won the pawn and has exchanged even more material.
White realized he didn't want to exchange material so he chose not to pursue the exchange(s) but then he forgot that his knight was en prise.
Now comes a series of pretty knight moves starting with check and a fork. White cannot save both his pawn on h2 and his bishop on f1 at this point - one of them will die.
I only need to move one space - if white follows he loses his bishop.
31. h3 was the wrong move for white. His bishop on f1 is now attacked twice and has nowhere to run.
The stall is no threat to black.
Final position. White has had enough.

Hi everyone!  Another tight middle game battle turns in my favour.  This time Glenda whose magic powers are sometimes as good as Mildred Hubble's in Jill Murphy's The Worst Witch manages to get into the enemy camp and turn a couple of enemy pawns into sludge before she exchanges herself for the Wicked Witch of the West.  I then manage to simplify further until Bob voluntarily enters a K & P ending.  What did I say about these endings when you are a pawn or more down in material?  Just don't go there......
4. e4 - a typically English opening - I now control the centre with e4 and try to discourage d5.  Both sides now develop their pieces over the next few moves.
7. 0-0 - an impressive white pawn centre Henry castled what more does a girl called Joanne want?

12. Ng5 - I return the compliment of black's 8th move.  This move puts the question to black's advanced steed on g4.  Black does not wish his pawn structure to be compromised so he retreats the knight.
16. ....... Bxf6 - one pair of knights exchanged.
19. Bd2 - development complete.
20. Qc1 - preparing a possible Bh6.
25. Qxb1 - one pair of rooks is exchanged and Glenda controls the b file.
26. Qb7 - Glenda dares venture into the enemy camp - she is attacking the loose pawn on a6 but .......
26. ........ Bc8! - ........ she is driven back.  The black lsb protects the pawn on a6 x-ray fashion.
29. Qb6 - If at first you don't succeed try try again!
31. ........ Bf6? - this retreat now transforms Glenda the Defender into Glenda the Offender.  One pawn drops .........
34. Qxe5 - ...... and another!
37. ........ Kxf8 - a same bishop ending two pawns up this game should definitely be in white's favour - time for Henry to emerge from the trenches ....... don't worry Henry the Wicked Witch is dead!
40. Kf4 - As far as Henry is concerned it is ...... Quick ....... March!
40. ......... a5 - tries for some queenside action but to no avail.
42. ......... Bf5 - this only delays the loss of the g pawn and gets me into that won K & P ending that jstevens1 strives for!
45. Kg7 - now Bob where do you want Glenda to re-appear?  d8 or h8?  Neither says Bob I surrender!  That's all for now folks!
This team match is probably one of my best games on GameKnot as I have sacrificed 4 times before checkmating my opponent in 24 moves.
Nimzo-indian defence classic variation.
4. ...0-0 or 4. ...d5 can also be played.
A very common position. Black still need to develop their knight and white bishop.
8. Bg5 can also be played but I prefer this variation as it is more attacking.
This simple move turned out to be decisive later on.
10. b4 and 10. e4 are possible options.
Until this moment the game has been played according to the opening. 11. ...f6 is a possibility along with Qc7.
This move was provocative - the bishop does not look dangerous but my opponent still wanted to attack it.
Not the best decision. There was no point in weakening the position of the king simply for attacking a bishop that poses no danger.
First sacrifice in this game. Black are already in a passive position but my advantage is not yet enough to win.
A mistake. 13. ...Rf7 or 13. ...Qe7 would have been better but black underestimate the power of white's attack. My opponent has wasted 4 moves attacking one bishop.
Black immediately try to swap their passive queen for my attacking one.
Evidently I avoid the change.
The bishop is moved to e4 in order to keep file D open for the rook.

Black are left with no options. 18. ...Ng7 would lead to 19. Qh7  and 20. Bg6#. There are other moves such as 18. ...hxg3 18. ...Qg7 or even 18. ...Nf4 but they all led to my victory. The situation on the board is already hopeless for black.
File G is now open for my attack. This move is much stronger than 19. Qxh5.
Last attempt to close down the bishop but it fails. White are in full control.

20. Nd5! - a simple but elegant move. Black can not take the bishop because they will lose their queen and the knight is also invincible because of 21. Rg1   Rg7 22. Bd5  Kf8 23. Qh8  Rg8 and 24. Rxg8#.
I think the only way to avoid immediate checkmate was by playing 20. ...Rg7 and giving the queen away.
21. Nf6 !  the fourth and the last sacrifice. At this stage I had already planned the checkmate and so my goal was to move the black rook from protecting g7.
No other moves left - black must accept.
Using the king's weakness to full potential. 22. ...Qg7 can not be played now. 22. ...Rg6 would have slowed the checkmate down to 6 moves.
23. ...Qg7 now leads to 24. Rxg7  Ke8 25. Rg8  Bf8 and 26. Qxd7.

The finishing touch. Two of my rooks on d1 and g1 are completely devastating. Having only one pawn advantage white are dominant. Although black have made plenty of mistakes this game's final is quite good looking.
To attack can be very dangerous... for the one who attacks. In a "thematic" Scandinavian Lasker variation.

Here the "winning" move for white is d5. It puts me under a real pressure since black cannot allow white to go to b5 with one of its minor pieces. The only time I faced an opponent who went for it I was crushed in a dozen games. Black doesn't have to take fxe5 and if white takes dxc6 black has to play very oddly bxc6 otherwise Nb5 and related moves are overwhelming. Maybe this is not completely accurate or oversimplified I admit.
I always say that the best move here for white is e5... but nobody makes it :-)
Saved from the e5 danger.
I am aware of the danger represented by the half-open e file and the possible sacs in d5 white has.
The knight goes for the bishop. Very well I lose a good bishop for a poor knight. But I have counterplay for that even if I have to lose a tempo for it.

Now white's pressure is balanced by my pressure against h2 and even if it is easy for white to defend he must start to figure out a plan while I am ready to castle queenside. The attack coming from a4 b4 etc. is something my experience says that I can cope with.
The other defence h3 is definitely better. It is not clear if it "destroys" my setting but it is better for sure. Because the three pawns can be taken even by pieces. A sacrifice is coming.

This way I risk. But in one move I put my rook in front of his queen that cannot get out easily. My knight is free to jump to e5 or c5. I know white will attack my queenside but in the meanwhile I will do the same on his kingside. With 11. h3 I better think in how to defend and normally I can (I have a good knight jump due to the pin of the d4 pawn in front of the white queen. It always worries white...).
Building the attack. Better seems Bf4 but I just had to choose between Bd6 or even e5 to defend.
Still developing. The black position seems to be very innocent due to underdevelopment.
First "strange" move. But it makes sense: releases the pin on the queen and adds pressure to the a and b pawns that soon will be launched against my king.

Now I am building up MY attack. And I am offering the knight for the white bishop if he accepts it it will release some strenght to the white force over my king... while my rook still aims at h2 and soon it will be ready to be supported by the other one.
Here he goes. I have one or two moves before I have really to take care of the queenside.

This is a very dangerous move. I always try to avoid it on this scheme because the weakness of e6 is often mortal. But in this case all my attack can vanishes after Ne4 so I have to avoid that. Yes I know the e column is easy to open for white. So will become the d column for me.

It makes me lose a tempo defending the rook while he is starting to open the e column... and leaving the d column to me. Moreover it "helps" me to get my piece over the kingside. No matter the knight is pinned as you will see.

Now I could have been almost "destroyed" by 16. Bc4 double-attacking e6. 
Anyway there are some compensations here: 
I can take the d pawn with my rook. 
After the check I can simply retire my king to b8. It IS in danger but my attack is going on. 
After the lsb moves I can jump with my knight to g4 adding material to my attack.
Releases the pressure on the e column maybe realizing what I commented before. But my aim is not to take the d pawn...
The gun is armed.
Back to the original a-b plan... less dangerous now without the dsb aiming at a7 (I will question this move). Anyway if Bc4 there is no problem for me. Not anymore.
I could swear he didn't expect this one.
And this. I am sacrificing TWO minor pieces but this is only apparent. After Qg3  I can take the bishop in g5 so...
Ok but not enough. From now on most variants go to mate the better for white with a piece less and a very bad position.
I could well have taken Rxe2 but I wanted to threaten Rxd4.

This game introduces me to the English Defense a response that Kosten seems to imply is underrated (esp considering it's only used in 1 out of 80 English openings!) and chessgames.com bears him out with black winning as often as white for games in their database.
The idea here is to fianchetto the QB the same as in a Queen's Indian Defense this of course would tend to counter the KB fianchetto of White's.
Unusual second move out of Kosten's book not the usual 2. g3.
Develops the QB.
This was the idea behind the second move to establish the KP at e4 this allows for the KB to develop without incident as well as reinforcing control of d5.
A reply not covered in Chapter 16 of Kosten's book.  His favored line for Black uses a 'hedgehog setup' with 3...c5.  Possibly this is a 'tit for tat' response to my 3. e4.
Develops the KN earlier than the text does now if Black plays 4...Bb4 then 5. a3 refutes.
Prepares to castle K-side.
Fianchettoes the KB.
White has very strong control of d5 at this point also has shared control of d4 due to Black's c-pawn hanging back.
This vies for control of d4 had I moved 7. d3 instead of castling could now counter with 8. Be3....
....instead I get my Q into the mix by playing 8. d4 counter to Kosten's strategy of securing the center with d3 then pawn-storming the K-side.
This of course invites an exchange of pawns...
....followed by an exchange of N's....
....with an ensuing conquest of the entire diagonal containing d4 by Black's KB!  This is a rather disappointing turn of events considering....
....my f-pawn is now pinned to my K and my pawn-storm must be put off for now!
Put off indefinitely is more like it as my insecure center appears to have attracted some notice by the opposition.

It's been a while since I've annotated a game; this is the first game I have finished in nearly two weeks. Tired of the old d5 I play something a little different. The Indian Defense.
2. e6 indicates that white might want to set up a Stonewall Attack. So I begin choosing moves that don't bang my head against that stone wall.

I'm offering white an opportunity to break up his own Stonewall with 6. pxc5 Qa5  and 7. ... Qxc5 and now his stone wall has a big hole in it.
White wasn't having it - he completes the "classic" Stonewall formation.

White saved what's left of his stones so now I get back on my e5 plan.

I'm not sure what 13. a4 was doing but it seems harmless enough and now I can't help but notice that the knight on b3 is undefended. Unfortunately I don't see a convenient way to remove the pawn on c3.
Exchanges abound.
Not much left of that wall now.
White's 17. Qh4 and that c3 pawn takes all the fun out of the fork.

If 19. Pxb4 then 19. ... Bxd4  and 20. ... Qxb4 and black has gained a pawn. Meanwhile I threaten the undefended bishop at d3 and a nice little fork at c2 (puts three pieces on White's pinned knight on d4).

White's 19. Be4 put the kabosh on all of my knight's threats so I play a simple move attacking the knight on d4. In retrospect I think now that 19. ... Bxd4  might have been more aggressive and would have won a pawn as well as creating opportunities to liquidate some pieces to exploit that material advantage.
Black has gained the bishop pair advantage though that's hardly decisive.

White unpinned the knight on d4 and black seizes an opportunity to fork the rook on f1 and the pawn on a4. Note that I don't plan on playing Bxa4 any time soon since that bishop would be pinned and easily won by white with b3.

22. Bh6 was a strong move by white. He linked his rooks defending the en prise rook on f1 and at the same time threatens to win the exchange by capturing Black's rook on f8. I didn't really see this coming and it became a thorn in my side for a several moves - but I vow that eventually white will pay the price for stationing his bishop so far from home.
Well there goes the bishop pair and now things look pretty much dead even. I don't know if white is playing for a draw but I certainly would not be satisfied with drawing.
White threatened the pawn at f7 with certain mate to follow. Black's queen rushes to the defense.
White played as expected pinning Black's bishop on e5. f6 saves the bishop from any future embarrassment and at the same time the bishop protects the pawn too.

White has a strong attack going 4 pieces bearing down on a broken castle with only 3 defenders. I was surprised he played 26. a5. My response threatens the pawn. I have to play carefully here though with White's strong attack.

White seems to have made his first mistake of the game. Black can safely take the pawn forking White's rook on e1 and the pawn on b4. It's important here that both the bishop and the queen remain on defensive duty to save the f6 pawn and the subsequent mate threats.

A welcome trade since black now has a winning material advantage. This also evened the number of attackers and defenders by exchanging white's strong rook part of his attack for black's weak rook that was far removed from defending.

White's 29. Qf4 seems to defend the pawn at b4 but the defense is an illusion for black takes the pawn anyway and now if 30. Qxb4??? then black wins instantly with 30. ... Qxf1  . 29. ... Bxb4 does allow white to play 30. Qxf6 but black's queen is still on defense so after 30. ... Qxf6 31. Rxf6??? Rf1  wins immediately for black.
And now my piece de resistance. My favorite move of the game. If White's queen moves away black wins the bishop on h6. If white captures Black's bishop he loses less material after 31. ... Qxf1 .
Remember that vow I made on my 22nd move?
The long range check is only a minor inconvenience now that the white bishop is gone from a6 and White's rook is still en prise on f1.

Rf2 insures that White's two remaining pieces defend each other and defend their remaining pawns too. But black has a combination that cracks White's defense open like an egg. With careful play white can squirm out of immediate loss (at least I didn't find a forced mating combination here) but even those lines allow black to exchange White's queen and rook and win easily with a bishop and two pawns advantage.
35. Rf3 saves White's game for now but after 35. Bg2  white is in serious trouble. As played white is now doomed.

Not a check white is not forced. But he has nothing. Black threatens mate on g1 and h1. The rook cannot protect both squares. 37. h4 loses to 37. ...Qh1  . White could try 37. Rc7  Bxc7 38. Qg2 to stop all the immediate checkmates but 38. ... Re2 wins White's queen and black mates in a few moves with his bishop and queen.

What about this game?
In OTB chess I haven't yet adopted my Gameknot policy of abandoning the KP openings against stronger players.
The Ruy Lopez or Spanish Opening the second opening I ever learnt after the Giuoco Piano.
The main alternative is the Spanish Exchange whereby White takes on c6 giving up his powerful Bishop to give Black doubled pawns.  The game develops very differently.
The Orthodox Defence

in which White allows Black to capture the e-pawn if she wants in return for an open centre and pressure down the open files.  Black normally declines the invitation in the interest of quick development.

The disadvantage of the Spanish from White's point of view is the time wasted fleeing Black's attacks on this Bishop.  The benefit of doing so is the power exercised by the Bishop along the diagonals a2-g8 and/or b1-h7.  This is seen in this game.  By attacking the B so quickly as in this game Black gets the opportunity to force a swap off by following up with 6... Na5.  Otherwise this move order tends to transpose to the main line.

Interesting!  As explained I was expecting 6...Na5 but Black sticks to opening principles avoiding moving a piece twice instead developing her QB on the long diagonal threatening not only to attack my B but also the e-pawn at the same time.  Looking this up in my old book on the Spanish by Alexei Suetin I find that this is the Archangel Variation or a modern version of the Mřller system.  I don't remember ever meeting this before.

I opt for a cautious approach defending the e-pawn with my d-pawn since I fear that Heather's tactical ability will over-power me if I adopt a sharper variation.  The only alternative I seriously considered was 7. c3 providing a hole for my B but I wasn't confident that I could cope with the tactical possibilities after 7...Na5 8. Bc2 Nxe4 9. Re1 d5 for example.  Suetin also considers 7. d4 7. Nc3 and 7. Re1 which all look weak to me but White probably has hidden resources.

? Shocking!  I've never seen such a bad opening move from such a good player.  Unsurprisingly this does not feature in Suetin's book.  I could only conclude that she was trying to encourage me to "teach her a lesson" and overstretch myself or that she planned 8 c3 Na5 9. Bc2 c5 and 10... Bc7.  The B belongs on e7 not blocking in the d-pawn but protecting the Nf6 from being pinned against his Q.
Resuming proper opening principles rather than following the plan I'd envisaged.

Normally with the Black B on e7 this B stays at home while the QN goes on a tour of the back ranks before emerging on e3 or g3 and then going to d5 or f5.  But in this position I'd defended e4 with d3 rather than Re1 so I wasn't yet ready for that tour.  Furthermore the Black B was out of position so I decided to exploit that with this move.
Naturally Black chases him away
I don't want to free Black's position by giving up the Bishop pair swapping my good B for her N allowing her to develop her Q to f6 which would partially justify her 7th move.

a sensible developing move which also allows the B to retreat to f8 as it does in the Breyer where Black also redevelops the QN via b8 to d7.  I seem to remember Spassky using that system against Fischer unsuccessfully.
continuing my development in the most flexible way.

Now it looks like Black will regain a tempo for her fianchetto by launching her g-pawn to g5 pushing my B back.  If I cooperate with her plan I'll have a horribly cramped position so I'm already thinking about taking on g5.  I haven't yet decided whether to sac the N or the B for two pawns though.  Both plans had their attractions with the f-pawn undefended and attacked by my Bb3 and with the potential to make the pin on the black diagonal permanent.
I make space for the QN to continue its tour if necessary meanwhile reinforcing e4 and preparing to contest the file if it opens up after either ...d5 or d4.

Queen's pawn opening.
http://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Chess/Queen%27s_Pawn_Opening
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queen%27s_Pawn_Game

The only thing I really want to point out is that the initial pawn is protected by the queen so there's no fear of an immediate attack against the pawn.

It's best to have a plan for developing your pieces to useful squares quickly.  The method both players use to do that is called the opening (I know that seems pretty basic).  

Try to concentrate of moving one or both central pawns to the center (top of the hill) develop both knights and bishops and castle by move 10.  That takes 7 moves leaving 3 for defending or retreating if a piece was moved too far out.

The most common 2nd move seems to be c4 which is the Queen's Gambit.  This move is passive in that it defends a piece that's already defended and not attacked but is a good development move in preparation for castling kingside.
Note that diagonal knights counter each other in the center.
This opens up the light squared bishop but confines the dark squared bishop.  It's still defensive in that the d4 pawn is now defended 3 times and attacked once.

The 3rd rank on the c and f files followed by the 2nd rank on the d and e files is the best development spots for the knights.  The edge of the board reduces the number of squares they can move do which greatly decreases their influence and power.

The 5th rank is usually a good place to develop a bishop because of the immediate pin on the knight.  Whether or not you end up exchanging the pieces is a matter of preference but the pin is what is important.

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pin_(chess)

Black should take immediate action to break the pin.  Recognizing taking advantage of and breaking pins are important skills to develop.  In this case it's obvious that black wants castle which would break the pin on the knight but castling isn't fast enough...
White should be looking at playing Ne5 to attack the pinned knight on c6.  That would force white to defend it again or risk losing material or a weakened pawn structure.

Black plays for a symmetrical position and pins white's knight.  Symmetrical positions tend to be better for the side with initiative (white at the beginning of the game).  This also opens up black's kingside for castling.
Attacking the pinned knight.
Black castles to break the pin but is a move too late.  Bd7 would have prevented any material loss but white would then have the option of exchanging his knight for black's bishop.
White exchanges to win a pawn.
White tries to break the pin on his knight by forcing the bishop to retreat.  Bd2 would have been better since an exchange wouldn't result in a weakened pawn structure.
Black exchanges rather than retreat.

White's queenside pawn structure fragments.  Isolated and doubled pawns are usually considered weak.  Notice that no pawns can help support the a and c pawns on either side so pieces must be used to defend them.  

Also note the open b file.  Both sides want them for control of the board but black has already claimed this one with his rook which will make it difficult for white to use it.

Ba6 would have been better since it would have prevented white from castling and cramped white on both sides of the board.

Move 10 is when both sides should have developed all minor pieces and castled.  Black is a little further along and has a couple small advantages at this point (rook posted on the b file and a centralized knight).

c4 would have been a better move.  Black's d pawn is pinned to his knight so he wouldn't be able to capture white's c pawn immediately and white could untangle his doubled c pawns by exchanging one or both of them away.

If black decided to play 11...Nc3 anyway 12. Qd3 would force Ne4 allowing 13. cxd5 exd5 14. c4 which forces Nf6 or wins a pawn.

Black seems to have an interesting plan here but I don't see a way for him to do more than win white's f pawn.  

I think Bd7 is better since it would force the exchange of white's active bishop and allow black to push his c pawn forward either tripling and isolating white's c pawns or pushing it to c4 to further weaken white's c pawns.  

Nxc3 is also an option if black wants to recover his pawn but I think it's a wasted move.

f3 is better.  It would protect the prevent black from capturing on f2 force black's knight to give up his outpost and support an e pawn advance in a few moves.  It would slightly weaken the king on g3 and along the a7-g1 diagonal but since black already gave up his dark squared bishop it's a minimal risk.

If black responds with Nxc3 then 13. Qd3 wins the knight.

An interesting attack.  If white hadn't already defended his f2 pawn this would have won it.  As it is it hampers white a little and forces his rook to the e file but if white could get rid of the knight on e4 then the e1 is where white's rook should be to support his e pawn as it opens files for attacking.

It also links black's rooks which would be good if he planned on doing anything with them.  I think Bb7 or Rb6 would both be slightly better.

Nxf6 would have been better because it would have left black's pawns intact.  

As pieces come off the board the king gets braver and braver.  With the closed position of the board and queens gone there's no reason that black's king needs to hide in the corner but protected pawns may be important later during the endgame.
White gets tired of black's knight dominating the center of the board.
Bxf1 would have been better but would have given white his choice of pieces to capture in exchange.  Black elected to save his knight and pick up a tasty snack on c3 which evens material.

This is a wasted move.  The knight can't do any real harm and has nowhere to no other than back to c3.  An exchange for the bishop would link white's rooks and get rid of white's weak bishop on black's time.

? - Bad move.  

Kf2 would move the king toward the center but most importantly it would prevent the discovered attack from white's bishop.

A better move is Nxd4  (discovered check) then followed it up with Nxc6.

Another option is Nxc1  followed by Ne2 which may lead to 18. Rxe2 Bxe2 19. Kxe2 winning a rook and bishop for bishop and knight but that gains less material as well as leaving white's active bishop in play.
Rxb5 is better.  It leave white with a passive bishop under attack by the knight and rook as well as "lift" black's rook and allow his 2nd one to link on the b file.

White's pawns are doubled again but this time the 2nd pawn actually strengthens white's center.  He could either trade his d4 pawn if black pushed his c pawn and still maintain a pawn front on the d and e files or support his e pawn during a push forward.

At this point both positions are almost identical.  Black's rook on the b file is easily countered and the differences in pawn structure are almost negligible.

Black should push his c pawn to exchange it since it's backwards (on a half open file and behind the adjacent pawn).  Backwards pawns can be difficult to defend and should be exchanged or pushed forward if possible.
This prevents black from pushing his pawn and binds black's rooks to defending it.  White
Ke3 would have defended white's pawns better though black could have played for a draw by alternating checks and attacks on white pawns.

White should keep his rook on the a file and try to advance that pawn to queen.  It's difficult to move the rook out of the way but with black's king on the 2nd rank it's possible.  Something like:
34. Ra8 f6 35. a6 e5 36. a7 Ra3  37. Kf2 Ra4 38. Rg8  Kh6 39. a8=Q Rxa8 40. Rxa8
White tries to prevent black's pawns from moving but allowing the e pawn to be pinned is a bad idea.  It would be better to advance his g and h pawns.
c5 taking advantage of white's pinned pawn would have been better.

Positions are almost equal again though white's single e pawn leaves him slightly weaker.

This game should draw barring any blunders.
exf5  is slightly better since it would link all 3 pawns.  Black's passed e pawn could be problematic if white gets careless but the risk is minor compared to the safety gained with protected pawns.

Re6 is better since it forces black's king to retreat or advance to g5 where things get confined and scary.

Note that black's pawns form a barrier that white's king has trouble passing.
White can't hold onto both his h and e pawns.
